<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>TF-4 Law of Sines and Cosines</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers setting up and solving problems using the Law 
      of Sines and the Law of Cosines. You should be able to draw a 
      diagram of the situation, label the sides and angles, and determine 
      which law to use to solve for the unknowns. 
      You should be able to write out complete steps to solve these 
      types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Set up and solve problems using the Law of Sines and the Law of Cosines. This includes identifying 
        which law to use based on the given information, setting up the appropriate equations, and solving 
        for the unknown sides or angles. You should be able to apply these laws to a variety of problems, 
        including those involving triangles in real-world contexts.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>
           Two ships leave a port at the same time.  One travels 34 mph in a direction <m>N35^{\circ}E</m> and 
           the other travels 32 mph in a direction <m>S42^{\circ}E</m>.  How far apart are the ships after 2 hours?
        </p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>How far apart are the ships after 2 hours?</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the Law of Cosines to set up the equation to find the distance between the ships.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>d=4\sqrt{545-544\cos103^{\circ}}</m> miles</p></answer>
            <solution><p>After drawing the diagram we find that the interior angle is <m>103^{\circ}</m>. 
              We can use the Law of Cosines to find the distance between the ships. Let 
              <m>d</m> be the distance between the ships, <m>a</m> be the distance traveled by the first 
              ship, and <m>b</m> be the distance traveled by the second ship. Then:</p>
            <p><m>d^2=a^2+b^2-2ab\cos C</m></p>
            <p>Where <m>C</m> is the angle between the two paths. In this case, 
              <m>C=103^{\circ}</m>, <m>a=68</m> miles (since the first ship travels 34 
              mph for 2 hours), and <m>b=64</m> miles (since the second ship travels 32 
              mph for 2 hours). Substituting these values:</p>
            <p><m>d^2=68^2+64^2-2(68)(64)\cos103^{\circ}</m></p>
            <p><m>d^2=4624+4096-2(68)(64)\cos103^{\circ}</m></p>
            <p><m>d^2=8720-544\cos103^{\circ}</m></p>
            <p><m>d=\sqrt{8720-544\cos103^{\circ}}</m></p>
            <p><m>d=4\sqrt{545-544\cos103^{\circ}}</m> miles</p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Two wires tether a balloon to the ground as shown in the following picture.
              Let <m>\alpha=65^{\circ}, \beta=78^{\circ}</m> and let <m>x=95ft.</m> 
            Use the law of sines or cosines to find the value of <m>h</m>, the height the balloon is 
            above the ground.  Leave your answer in a simplified exact form.</p>
          <figure>
            <caption>Balloon tethered by two wires</caption>
            <image source="Balloon_Problem.png"/>
          </figure>
          </statement> 
              <hint><p>Use the law of sines to find the hypotenuse of the inner triangle. Then use
                right triangle trigonometry to find the height.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>h=\frac{95\sin65^{\circ}\sin78^{\circ}}{\sin13^{\circ}}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>First, we use the law of sines to find the hypotenuse of the inner triangle.
              <m>\frac{\sin65^{\circ}}{y}=\frac{\sin13^{\circ}}{95}</m>
              Solving for <m>y</m>:
              <m>y=\frac{95\sin65^{\circ}}{\sin13^{\circ}}</m>
              Then, we use right triangle trigonometry to find the height of the balloon.
            <m>\sin78^{\circ}=\frac{h}{y}</m>
            <m>h=y\sin78^{\circ}</m>
            <m>h=\frac{95\sin65^{\circ}\sin78^{\circ}}{\sin13^{\circ}}</m> ft</p></solution>
        </task>
        
    </exercise>
   
  </page>
</worksheet>